‚≠ï What is RAM (Random Access Memory)?
Ram is the high-speed, temporary storage used by computers to hold data for active applications, operating systems, and documents, distinct from permanent storage like HDDs or SSDs.

‚ú¥Ô∏è Key Technical Characteristics
*Ô∏è‚É£ DRAM (Dynamic RAM): The most common type of RAM. It is "dynamic" because it must be constantly refreshed with power to prevent data loss.
*Ô∏è‚É£ Synchronous DRAM (SDRAM): The memory is synchronized with the system clock, allowing all components to know precisely when data will be available.
*Ô∏è‚É£ Random Access: Any piece of data can be read directly without reading through all preceding data (unlike a tape).

‚ú¥Ô∏è Memory Module Types
‚ùáÔ∏è DIMM (Dual In-line Memory Module)
‚ùó Description: Standard full-size RAM module for desktops and servers; "dual in-line" refers to offset connectors on front/back for secure insertion.
‚ùó Size: Larger form factor (about 5.25 inches long).
‚ùó Installation: Aligns with motherboard slots; push lightly until clips lock on both ends to prevent accidental removal.
‚ùó Uses: Desktops, workstations; supports high capacities for demanding tasks.

‚ùáÔ∏è SO-DIMM (Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module)
‚ùó Description: Compact version of DIMM, about half the width (2.66 inches long).
‚ùó Installation: Similar to DIMM but in smaller laptop slots; pushes down and locks with clips.
‚ùó Uses: Laptops, tablets, and small form-factor devices where space is limited.

üìõ Comparison: Physically smaller than DIMM but functionally similar; both use the same DDR standards.

‚ö° Data Transfer Mechanisms:
‚ú≥Ô∏è SDR (Legacy): One data block per clock cycle (e.g., rising edge only)‚Äîobsolete now.
‚ú≥Ô∏è DDR (Modern): Doubles transfers per cycle (rising + falling edges) for better speed without higher clocks.

